[2]
Date: 9 Feb 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: El Diario [translated and edited by Mod. MPP]
<http://www.eldiario.net/>

Outbreak of malaria in Guanay and in Palos Blancos
------------------------------------------------
According to reports of the Departmental Health Service (SEDES) on the
malaria outbreak in the province of La Paz, 110 cases of malaria have
presented in the region of Palos Blancos (South Yungas) and 12 in the rural
region of Guanay. This was announced by the prefecture of the province,
German Velasco.
"The malaria outbreak is in the early stages when it can be controlled.
This should not lead to panic, but it does require immediate attention. We
are now in the middle of controllable activity," [said Velasco]. He
explained that the outbreak reported in Palos Blancos was not a result of
the intense rains and for this reason Palos Blancos would not be treated as
a disaster zone. As Palos Blancos is in a malaria endemic zone, this
disease outbreak was a predictable outcome of the recent flooding.
According to the same reports of SEDES La Paz, there is a suspect case of
dengue in the north of the province. In an attempt to cover all of the
patients in the zone, 2 medical teams with [about] 30 physicians will be
transported to this region of the province [on] Monday morning [12 Feb
2001], and will replace the medical team installed there for the past
several weeks.
